{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":2000,"text":"Thank you. It's really an honor and a privilege to be here"},{"time":6000,"text":"spending my last day as a teenager."},{"time":8000,"text":"Today I want to talk to you about the future, but"},{"time":12000,"text":"first I'm going to tell you a bit about the past."},{"time":15000,"text":"My story starts way before I was born."},{"time":19000,"text":"My grandmother was on a train to Auschwitz, the death camp."},{"time":23000,"text":"And she was going along the tracks, and the tracks split."},{"time":28000,"text":"And somehow -- we don't really know exactly the whole story -- but"},{"time":33000,"text":"the train took the wrong track and went to a work camp rather than the death camp."},{"time":38000,"text":"My grandmother survived and married my grandfather."},{"time":43000,"text":"They were living in Hungary, and my mother was born."},{"time":46000,"text":"And when my mother was two years old,"},{"time":48000,"text":"the Hungarian revolution was raging, and they decided to escape Hungary."},{"time":53000,"text":"They got on a boat, and yet another divergence --"},{"time":57000,"text":"the boat was either going to Canada or to Australia."},{"time":60000,"text":"They got on and didn't know where they were going, and ended up in Canada."},{"time":64000,"text":"So, to make a long story short, they came to Canada."},{"time":67000,"text":"My grandmother was a chemist. She worked at the Banting Institute in Toronto,"},{"time":71000,"text":"and at 44 she died of stomach cancer. I never met my grandmother,"},{"time":79000,"text":"but I carry on her name -- her exact name, Eva Vertes --"},{"time":83000,"text":"and I like to think I carry on her scientific passion, too."}]},{"cues":[{"time":87000,"text":"I found this passion not far from here, actually, when I was nine years old."},{"time":93000,"text":"My family was on a road trip and we were in the Grand Canyon."},{"time":98000,"text":"And I had never been a reader when I was young --"},{"time":101000,"text":"my dad had tried me with the Hardy Boys; I tried Nancy Drew;"},{"time":104000,"text":"I tried all that -- and I just didn't like reading books."},{"time":108000,"text":"And my mother bought this book when we were at the Grand Canyon"},{"time":112000,"text":"called \"The Hot Zone.\" It was all about the outbreak of the Ebola virus."},{"time":115000,"text":"And something about it just kind of drew me towards it."},{"time":118000,"text":"There was this big sort of bumpy-looking virus on the cover,"},{"time":121000,"text":"and I just wanted to read it. I picked up that book,"},{"time":125000,"text":"and as we drove from the edge of the Grand Canyon"},{"time":128000,"text":"to Big Sur, and to, actually, here where we are today, in Monterey,"},{"time":131000,"text":"I read that book, and from when I was reading that book,"},{"time":136000,"text":"I knew that I wanted to have a life in medicine."},{"time":139000,"text":"I wanted to be like the explorers I'd read about in the book,"},{"time":142000,"text":"who went into the jungles of Africa,"},{"time":144000,"text":"went into the research labs and just tried to figure out"},{"time":146000,"text":"what this deadly virus was. So from that moment on, I read every medical book"},{"time":152000,"text":"I could get my hands on, and I just loved it so much."},{"time":156000,"text":"I was a passive observer of the medical world."}]},{"cues":[{"time":160000,"text":"It wasn't until I entered high school that I thought,"},{"time":164000,"text":"\"Maybe now, you know -- being a big high school kid --"},{"time":167000,"text":"I can maybe become an active part of this big medical world.\""},{"time":172000,"text":"I was 14, and I emailed professors at the local university"},{"time":177000,"text":"to see if maybe I could go work in their lab. And hardly anyone responded."},{"time":182000,"text":"But I mean, why would they respond to a 14-year-old, anyway?"},{"time":186000,"text":"And I got to go talk to one professor, Dr. Jacobs,"},{"time":190000,"text":"who accepted me into the lab."},{"time":193000,"text":"At that time, I was really interested in neuroscience"},{"time":196000,"text":"and wanted to do a research project in neurology --"},{"time":199000,"text":"specifically looking at the effects of heavy metals on the developing nervous system."},{"time":204000,"text":"So I started that, and worked in his lab for a year,"},{"time":209000,"text":"and found the results that I guess you'd expect to find"},{"time":213000,"text":"when you feed fruit flies heavy metals -- that it really, really impaired the nervous system."},{"time":218000,"text":"The spinal cord had breaks. The neurons were crossing in every which way."},{"time":222000,"text":"And from then I wanted to look not at impairment, but at prevention of impairment."}]},{"cues":[{"time":227000,"text":"So that's what led me to Alzheimer's. I started reading about Alzheimer's"},{"time":233000,"text":"and tried to familiarize myself with the research,"},{"time":236000,"text":"and at the same time when I was in the --"},{"time":238000,"text":"I was reading in the medical library one day, and I read this article"},{"time":241000,"text":"about something called \"purine derivatives.\""},{"time":243000,"text":"And they seemed to have cell growth-promoting properties."},{"time":248000,"text":"And being naive about the whole field, I kind of thought,"},{"time":251000,"text":"\"Oh, you have cell death in Alzheimer's"},{"time":253000,"text":"which is causing the memory deficit, and then you have this compound --"},{"time":258000,"text":"purine derivatives -- that are promoting cell growth.\""},{"time":260000,"text":"And so I thought, \"Maybe if it can promote cell growth,"},{"time":263000,"text":"it can inhibit cell death, too.\""},{"time":265000,"text":"And so that's the project that I pursued for that year,"},{"time":268000,"text":"and it's continuing now as well,"},{"time":271000,"text":"and found that a specific purine derivative called \"guanidine\""},{"time":276000,"text":"had inhibited the cell growth by approximately 60 percent."},{"time":279000,"text":"So I presented those results at the International Science Fair,"},{"time":283000,"text":"which was just one of the most amazing experiences of my life."},{"time":287000,"text":"And there I was awarded \"Best in the World in Medicine,\""},{"time":290000,"text":"which allowed me to get in, or at least get a foot in the door of the big medical world."}]},{"cues":[{"time":297000,"text":"And from then on, since I was now in this huge exciting world,"},{"time":303000,"text":"I wanted to explore it all. I wanted it all at once, but knew I couldn't really get that."},{"time":308000,"text":"And I stumbled across something called \"cancer stem cells.\""},{"time":310000,"text":"And this is really what I want to talk to you about today -- about cancer."},{"time":314000,"text":"At first when I heard of cancer stem cells,"},{"time":318000,"text":"I didn't really know how to put the two together. I'd heard of stem cells,"},{"time":322000,"text":"and I'd heard of them as the panacea of the future --"},{"time":325000,"text":"the therapy of many diseases to come in the future, perhaps."},{"time":328000,"text":"But I'd heard of cancer as the most feared disease of our time,"},{"time":332000,"text":"so how did the good and bad go together?"},{"time":336000,"text":"Last summer I worked at Stanford University, doing some research on cancer stem cells."},{"time":342000,"text":"And while I was doing this, I was reading the cancer literature,"},{"time":345000,"text":"trying to -- again -- familiarize myself with this new medical field."},{"time":350000,"text":"And it seemed that tumors actually begin from a stem cell."},{"time":358000,"text":"This fascinated me. The more I read, the more I looked at cancer differently"},{"time":365000,"text":"and almost became less fearful of it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":368000,"text":"It seems that cancer is a direct result to injury."},{"time":373000,"text":"If you smoke, you damage your lung tissue, and then lung cancer arises."},{"time":378000,"text":"If you drink, you damage your liver, and then liver cancer occurs."},{"time":383000,"text":"And it was really interesting -- there were articles correlating"},{"time":386000,"text":"if you have a bone fracture, and then bone cancer arises."},{"time":389000,"text":"Because what stem cells are -- they're these"},{"time":393000,"text":"phenomenal cells that really have the ability to differentiate"},{"time":397000,"text":"into any type of tissue."},{"time":399000,"text":"So, if the body is sensing that you have damage to an organ"},{"time":404000,"text":"and then it's initiating cancer, it's almost as if this is a repair response."},{"time":409000,"text":"And the cancer, the body is saying the lung tissue is damaged,"},{"time":414000,"text":"we need to repair the lung. And cancer is originating in the lung"},{"time":418000,"text":"trying to repair -- because you have this excessive proliferation"},{"time":422000,"text":"of these remarkable cells that really have the potential to become lung tissue."},{"time":427000,"text":"But it's almost as if the body has originated this ingenious response,"},{"time":431000,"text":"but can't quite control it."},{"time":433000,"text":"It hasn't yet become fine-tuned enough to finish what has been initiated."},{"time":438000,"text":"So this really, really fascinated me."}]},{"cues":[{"time":441000,"text":"And I really think that we can't think about cancer --"},{"time":446000,"text":"let alone any disease -- in such black-and-white terms."},{"time":449000,"text":"If we eliminate cancer the way we're trying to do now, with chemotherapy and radiation,"},{"time":455000,"text":"we're bombarding the body or the cancer with toxins, or with radiation, trying to kill it."},{"time":460000,"text":"It's almost as if we're getting back to this starting point."},{"time":463000,"text":"We're removing the cancer cells, but we're revealing the previous damage"},{"time":468000,"text":"that the body has tried to fix."},{"time":470000,"text":"Shouldn't we think about manipulation, rather than elimination?"},{"time":475000,"text":"If somehow we can cause these cells to differentiate --"},{"time":479000,"text":"to become bone tissue, lung tissue, liver tissue,"},{"time":482000,"text":"whatever that cancer has been put there to do --"},{"time":485000,"text":"it would be a repair process. We'd end up better than we were before cancer."},{"time":494000,"text":"So, this really changed my view of looking at cancer."},{"time":498000,"text":"And while I was reading all these articles about cancer,"},{"time":503000,"text":"it seemed that the articles -- a lot of them -- focused on, you know,"},{"time":505000,"text":"the genetics of breast cancer, and the genesis"},{"time":507000,"text":"and the progression of breast cancer --"},{"time":509000,"text":"tracking the cancer through the body, tracing where it is, where it goes."}]},{"cues":[{"time":515000,"text":"But it struck me that I'd never heard of cancer of the heart,"},{"time":520000,"text":"or cancer of any skeletal muscle for that matter."},{"time":523000,"text":"And skeletal muscle constitutes 50 percent of our body,"},{"time":527000,"text":"or over 50 percent of our body. And so at first I kind of thought,"},{"time":532000,"text":"\"Well, maybe there's some obvious explanation"},{"time":534000,"text":"why skeletal muscle doesn't get cancer -- at least not that I know of.\""},{"time":538000,"text":"So, I looked further into it, found as many articles as I could,"},{"time":543000,"text":"and it was amazing -- because it turned out that it was very rare."},{"time":547000,"text":"Some articles even went as far as to say that skeletal muscle tissue"},{"time":551000,"text":"is resistant to cancer, and furthermore, not only to cancer,"},{"time":556000,"text":"but of metastases going to skeletal muscle."},{"time":560000,"text":"And what metastases are is when the tumor --"},{"time":563000,"text":"when a piece -- breaks off and travels through the blood stream"},{"time":566000,"text":"and goes to a different organ. That's what a metastasis is."},{"time":570000,"text":"It's the part of cancer that is the most dangerous."},{"time":573000,"text":"If cancer was localized, we could likely remove it,"},{"time":576000,"text":"or somehow -- you know, it's contained. It's very contained."},{"time":580000,"text":"But once it starts moving throughout the body, that's when it becomes deadly."},{"time":583000,"text":"So the fact that not only did cancer not seem to originate in skeletal muscles,"},{"time":588000,"text":"but cancer didn't seem to go to skeletal muscle --"},{"time":591000,"text":"there seemed to be something here."},{"time":593000,"text":"So these articles were saying, you know, \"Skeletal --"},{"time":595000,"text":"metastasis to skeletal muscle -- is very rare.\""},{"time":598000,"text":"But it was left at that. No one seemed to be asking why."}]},{"cues":[{"time":602000,"text":"So I decided to ask why. At first -- the first thing I did"},{"time":609000,"text":"was I emailed some professors who"},{"time":611000,"text":"specialized in skeletal muscle physiology, and pretty much said,"},{"time":614000,"text":"\"Hey, it seems like cancer doesn't really go to skeletal muscle."},{"time":620000,"text":"Is there a reason for this?\" And a lot of the replies I got were that"},{"time":624000,"text":"muscle is terminally differentiated tissue."},{"time":628000,"text":"Meaning that you have muscle cells, but they're not dividing,"},{"time":631000,"text":"so it doesn't seem like a good target for cancer to hijack."},{"time":635000,"text":"But then again, this fact that the metastases"},{"time":638000,"text":"didn't go to skeletal muscle made that seem unlikely."},{"time":642000,"text":"And furthermore, that nervous tissue -- brain -- gets cancer,"},{"time":647000,"text":"and brain cells are also terminally differentiated."},{"time":650000,"text":"So I decided to ask why. And here's some of, I guess, my hypotheses"},{"time":656000,"text":"that I'll be starting to investigate this May at the Sylvester Cancer Institute in Miami."},{"time":665000,"text":"And I guess I'll keep investigating until I get the answers."},{"time":670000,"text":"But I know that in science, once you get the answers,"},{"time":673000,"text":"inevitably you're going to have more questions."},{"time":675000,"text":"So I guess you could say that I'll probably be doing this for the rest of my life."}]},{"cues":[{"time":680000,"text":"Some of my hypotheses are that"},{"time":683000,"text":"when you first think about skeletal muscle,"},{"time":686000,"text":"there's a lot of blood vessels going to skeletal muscle."},{"time":689000,"text":"And the first thing that makes me think is that"},{"time":693000,"text":"blood vessels are like highways for the tumor cells."},{"time":696000,"text":"Tumor cells can travel through the blood vessels."},{"time":698000,"text":"And you think, the more highways there are in a tissue,"},{"time":702000,"text":"the more likely it is to get cancer or to get metastases."},{"time":706000,"text":"So first of all I thought, you know, \"Wouldn't it be favorable"},{"time":709000,"text":"to cancer getting to skeletal muscle?\" And as well,"},{"time":712000,"text":"cancer tumors require a process called angiogenesis,"},{"time":717000,"text":"which is really, the tumor recruits the blood vessels to itself"},{"time":721000,"text":"to supply itself with nutrients so it can grow."},{"time":724000,"text":"Without angiogenesis, the tumor remains the size of a pinpoint and it's not harmful."},{"time":731000,"text":"So angiogenesis is really a central process to the pathogenesis of cancer."}]},{"cues":[{"time":737000,"text":"And one article that really stood out to me"},{"time":740000,"text":"when I was just reading about this, trying to figure out why cancer doesn't go to skeletal"},{"time":744000,"text":"muscle, was that it had reported 16 percent of micro-metastases"},{"time":751000,"text":"to skeletal muscle upon autopsy."},{"time":753000,"text":"16 percent! Meaning that there were these pinpoint tumors in skeletal muscle,"},{"time":758000,"text":"but only .16 percent of actual metastases --"},{"time":763000,"text":"suggesting that maybe skeletal muscle is able to control the angiogenesis,"},{"time":769000,"text":"is able to control the tumors recruiting these blood vessels."},{"time":774000,"text":"We use skeletal muscles so much. It's the one portion of our body --"},{"time":779000,"text":"our heart's always beating. We're always moving our muscles."},{"time":782000,"text":"Is it possible that muscle somehow intuitively knows"},{"time":786000,"text":"that it needs this blood supply? It needs to be constantly contracting,"},{"time":790000,"text":"so therefore it's almost selfish. It's grabbing its blood vessels for itself."},{"time":793000,"text":"Therefore, when a tumor comes into skeletal muscle tissue,"},{"time":797000,"text":"it can't get a blood supply, and can't grow."}]},{"cues":[{"time":800000,"text":"So this suggests that maybe if there is an anti-angiogenic factor"},{"time":805000,"text":"in skeletal muscle -- or perhaps even more,"},{"time":807000,"text":"an angiogenic routing factor, so it can actually direct where the blood vessels grow --"},{"time":812000,"text":"this could be a potential future therapy for cancer."},{"time":816000,"text":"And another thing that's really interesting is that"},{"time":821000,"text":"there's this whole -- the way tumors move throughout the body,"},{"time":825000,"text":"it's a very complex system -- and there's something called the chemokine network."},{"time":829000,"text":"And chemokines are essentially chemical attractants,"},{"time":833000,"text":"and they're the stop and go signals for cancer."},{"time":836000,"text":"So a tumor expresses chemokine receptors,"},{"time":841000,"text":"and another organ -- a distant organ somewhere in the body --"},{"time":844000,"text":"will have the corresponding chemokines,"},{"time":846000,"text":"and the tumor will see these chemokines and migrate towards it."},{"time":850000,"text":"Is it possible that skeletal muscle doesn't express this type of molecules?"},{"time":855000,"text":"And the other really interesting thing is that"},{"time":858000,"text":"when skeletal muscle -- there's been several reports that when skeletal"},{"time":862000,"text":"muscle is injured, that's what correlates with metastases going to skeletal muscle."}]},{"cues":[{"time":869000,"text":"And, furthermore, when skeletal muscle is injured,"},{"time":872000,"text":"that's what causes chemokines -- these signals saying,"},{"time":876000,"text":"\"Cancer, you can come to me,\" the \"go signs\" for the tumors --"},{"time":880000,"text":"it causes them to highly express these chemokines."},{"time":884000,"text":"So, there's so much interplay here."},{"time":891000,"text":"I mean, there are so many possibilities"},{"time":893000,"text":"for why tumors don't go to skeletal muscle."},{"time":896000,"text":"But it seems like by investigating, by attacking cancer,"},{"time":900000,"text":"by searching where cancer is not, there has got to be something --"},{"time":904000,"text":"there's got to be something -- that's making this tissue resistant to tumors."},{"time":910000,"text":"And can we utilize -- can we take this property,"},{"time":913000,"text":"this compound, this receptor, whatever it is that's controlling these"},{"time":917000,"text":"anti-tumor properties and apply it to cancer therapy in general?"},{"time":924000,"text":"Now, one thing that kind of ties the resistance of skeletal muscle to cancer --"},{"time":932000,"text":"to the cancer as a repair response gone out of control in the body --"},{"time":937000,"text":"is that skeletal muscle has a factor in it called \"MyoD.\""},{"time":945000,"text":"And what MyoD essentially does is, it causes cells to differentiate"},{"time":950000,"text":"into muscle cells. So this compound, MyoD,"},{"time":955000,"text":"has been tested on a lot of different cell types and been shown to"},{"time":959000,"text":"actually convert this variety of cell types into skeletal muscle cells."},{"time":963000,"text":"So, is it possible that the tumor cells are going to the skeletal muscle tissue,"},{"time":969000,"text":"but once in contact inside the skeletal muscle tissue,"},{"time":973000,"text":"MyoD acts upon these tumor cells and causes them"},{"time":978000,"text":"to become skeletal muscle cells?"},{"time":981000,"text":"Maybe tumor cells are being disguised as skeletal muscle cells,"},{"time":984000,"text":"and this is why it seems as if it is so rare."}]},{"cues":[{"time":989000,"text":"It's not harmful; it has just repaired the muscle."},{"time":992000,"text":"Muscle is constantly being used -- constantly being damaged."},{"time":995000,"text":"If every time we tore a muscle"},{"time":998000,"text":"or every time we stretched a muscle or moved in a wrong way,"},{"time":1001000,"text":"cancer occurred -- I mean, everybody would have cancer almost."},{"time":1008000,"text":"And I hate to say that. But it seems as though muscle cell,"},{"time":1012000,"text":"possibly because of all its use, has adapted"},{"time":1015000,"text":"faster than other body tissues to respond to injury,"},{"time":1018000,"text":"to fine-tune this repair response and actually be able to finish the process"},{"time":1024000,"text":"which the body wants to finish. I really believe that the human body is very,"},{"time":1029000,"text":"very smart, and we can't counteract something the body is saying to do."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1035000,"text":"It's different when a bacteria comes into the body --"},{"time":1038000,"text":"that's a foreign object -- we want that out."},{"time":1042000,"text":"But when the body is actually initiating a process"},{"time":1044000,"text":"and we're calling it a disease, it doesn't seem as though elimination is"},{"time":1048000,"text":"the right solution. So even to go from there, it's possible, although far-fetched,"},{"time":1056000,"text":"that in the future we could almost think of cancer being used as a therapy."},{"time":1063000,"text":"If those diseases where tissues are deteriorating --"},{"time":1066000,"text":"for example Alzheimer's, where the brain, the brain cells, die"},{"time":1071000,"text":"and we need to restore new brain cells, new functional brain cells --"},{"time":1075000,"text":"what if we could, in the future, use cancer? A tumor --"},{"time":1079000,"text":"put it in the brain and cause it to differentiate into brain cells?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1084000,"text":"That's a very far-fetched idea, but I really believe that it may be possible."},{"time":1090000,"text":"These cells are so versatile, these cancer cells are so versatile --"},{"time":1094000,"text":"we just have to manipulate them in the right way."},{"time":1097000,"text":"And again, some of these may be far-fetched, but"},{"time":1101000,"text":"I figured if there's anywhere to present far-fetched ideas, it's here at TED, so"},{"time":1106000,"text":"thank you very much."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1108000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}